DOCK Software Testing & Quality Assurance

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Architecture

    The $DOCK_HOME/install/test subdirectories are names of programs or
names of tests in the case of multi-program tests.  The general structure
and implementation is similar to that of the src build procedure and
employs make files.  The main advantages are simplicity, clarity,
localization of test information, and usage of ubiquitous tools.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
dockdif

    The output file diff-er is a simple script that eliminates common
sources of trivial differences.  It indicates pass or possible failure
on the standard output, and in the latter case creates a file of the
differences that has a .dif extension.
By convention, the .save extension denotes a reference output file.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Adding New Tests

    Testing of the non-DOCK DOCK programs employ simple make rules.
The file test/default_targets.h contains simple rules to test the
programs grid, sphgen, etc.

    To create a new test, copy the input files to an appropriate test
subdirectory renaming the files if necessary to adhere to the standard
input file names, copy the output files to the same subdirectory renaming
the files both to adhere to the standard names and to append the .save
extension, edit the Makefile to add a new target for the test and to
add the new test to the test target.

    Testing of the DOCK program employs make inference rules.
A make inference rule lists a generic recipe that is controlled by
file extensions.  For the DOCK program the inference rule gives an
algorithm to create a file with extension .dockout from a file with
extension .dockin.  To keep it simple this rule also runs the output
file diff-er; an alternative would be another inference rule to create
a .dif file from a .dockout file.  Consequently, the creation of an
input file and a reference output file are sufficient to create a new
test.  Such a new test would be run via make newtestname.  To place a
new test into the QC suite one must edit the Makefile for the appropriate
program and add newtestname to the test target.  If the new test requires
non-.dockin inputs then a new target called newtestname must be added to
specify the dependencies.

Here's the recipe to create a DOCK test:
1.  copy the dock input file to test/some_subdir/newtestname.dockin
2.  edit test/some_subdir/Makefile and add to the test target
    newtestname.dockout
2a. if the new test requires other inputs, such as grid files that are
    produced via another test, then create a new target called newtestname
    and list the other inputs as dependencies; also list newtestname.dockout
    as the last dependency and change the test target so that it contains
    newtestname instead of newtestname.dockout
3.  copy the reference output file to
    test/some_subdir/newtestname.dockout.save

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Updating The Reference Outputs of Tests

    $DOCK_HOME/install/test/update
is a script that automates the copying of a fresh output to the reference
output.  It takes a sed regular expression as an argument and searches
all the .dif files for that rexp.  The gold-standard platform for
reference outputs is hamlet with configuration file gnu.

Naturally, the utmost care should be used when modifying the reference
outputs.  One should verify their work not once, not twice, but thrice.
Furthermore, detailed CVS log messages are required; they should include
the reason for the modification.

Using a platform other than hamlet to generate the reference outputs
is strongly discouraged.  But if a different platform is used then the cvs
log should contain the machine name, the config file,
and the versions of any softwares employed, such as, the operating system,
the compiler, libraries, etc.

